). Forewing length 
<quantity id="CC54A1A82668FFC4FD12ADDFB91FFA7B" box="[748,868,1449,1473]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" unit="mm" value="10.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="10.0">10–11 mm</quantity>
. Head (including antennae and labial palpi), thorax (including legs) and abdomen colored as forewing. Eyes dark-brown, glabrous. Labial palpi twice longer than eyes in frontal view, antennae shorter than forewing length. Forewings upperside whitish-cream or whitish-yellow with slightly darker blurred submarginal line and small distinct brownish dot on discal vein. Hindwing slightly lighter than forewing, with slightly darker median band and slightly darker marginal border. Underside of both wings of same color and pattern as upperside. Fringes whitish-yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0B130C4D2668FFC4FF39AEF7BBFCF923" blockId="0.[151,1437,1236,2013]" box="[199,391,1665,1689]" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">Female unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0B130C4D2668FFC4FF39AED3B99CF893" blockId="0.[151,1437,1236,2013]" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2668FFC4FF39AED3BBA1F907" box="[199,474,1701,1725]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" reason="1">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2668FFC4FF39AED3BB1DF907" bold="true" box="[199,358,1701,1725]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="939710C82668FFC4FE8AAED3BBB6F907" box="[372,461,1701,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-19@1.[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Scoparia juldusellus. 1—male, Kara-Buura River valley; 2—male, Dolon Pass; 3—male genitalia, Kara-Buura valley, ventral view (aedeagus removed); 4—the same, aedeagus; 5, 6—habitats in Kyrgyzstan (5—Dolon Pass, Inner Tien- Shan; 6—Kara-Buura River valley, West Tien-Shan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457244" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457244/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">figs 3, 4</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Uncus triangular. Gnathos narrow and straight, longer than uncus, with pointed apex. Saccus massive, trapezoid. Valva wide, oblong-oval, with narrowly sclerotized dorsal margin; widely sclerotized sacculus with long and protruding acicular process apically. Aedeagus straight, slightly curved in its basal part, with single cornutus in form of long and heavily sclerotized thorn. Juxta thin, bilobed, C-shaped.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0B130C4D2668FFC4FF39AF43BFE2F8CB" blockId="0.[151,1437,1236,2013]" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2668FFC4FF39AF43BB4FF8F7" box="[199,308,1845,1869]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" reason="1">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2668FFC4FF39AF43BB56F8F7" bold="true" box="[199,301,1845,1869]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">Variation</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The specimen from West Tian-Shan (
<figureCitation id="939710C82668FFC4FD30AF43B97CF8F7" box="[718,775,1845,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-19@1.[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Scoparia juldusellus. 1—male, Kara-Buura River valley; 2—male, Dolon Pass; 3—male genitalia, Kara-Buura valley, ventral view (aedeagus removed); 4—the same, aedeagus; 5, 6—habitats in Kyrgyzstan (5—Dolon Pass, Inner Tien- Shan; 6—Kara-Buura River valley, West Tien-Shan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457244" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457244/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">fig. 1</figureCitation>
) is darker, with larger discal dot; the Inner Tian-Shanian one (
<figureCitation id="939710C82668FFC4FF61AF2FBAA2F8CB" box="[159,217,1881,1905]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-19@1.[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Scoparia juldusellus. 1—male, Kara-Buura River valley; 2—male, Dolon Pass; 3—male genitalia, Kara-Buura valley, ventral view (aedeagus removed); 4—the same, aedeagus; 5, 6—habitats in Kyrgyzstan (5—Dolon Pass, Inner Tien- Shan; 6—Kara-Buura River valley, West Tien-Shan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457244" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457244/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">fig. 2</figureCitation>
) is lighter, with more indistinct wing pattern. There are no differences in male genitalia between these specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="43B65FC62668FFC4FF39AF0BB8FAF867" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0B130C4D2668FFC4FF39AF0BB8FAF867" blockId="0.[151,1437,1236,2013]" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2668FFC4FF39AF0BBB58F82F" box="[199,291,1917,1941]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" reason="1">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2668FFC4FF39AF0BBB60F82F" bold="true" box="[199,283,1917,1941]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">Biology</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The species had been collected at light in two different river valleys: at the altitude about 
<quantity id="CC54A1A82668FFC4FB21AF0BBF4BF82F" box="[1247,1328,1917,1941]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" unit="m" value="2800.0">2800 m</quantity>
in the dry stony meadow slopes without bushes in Inner Tian-Shan (
<figureCitation id="939710C82668FFC4FCFFAFD7B940F803" box="[769,827,1953,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-19@1.[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Scoparia juldusellus. 1—male, Kara-Buura River valley; 2—male, Dolon Pass; 3—male genitalia, Kara-Buura valley, ventral view (aedeagus removed); 4—the same, aedeagus; 5, 6—habitats in Kyrgyzstan (5—Dolon Pass, Inner Tien- Shan; 6—Kara-Buura River valley, West Tien-Shan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457244" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457244/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">fig. 5</figureCitation>
) and at the altitude about 
<quantity id="CC54A1A82668FFC4FBACAFD7BED8F803" box="[1106,1187,1953,1977]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="0" pageNumber="597" unit="m" value="1700.0">1700 m</quantity>
in the dry stony steppe slopes with bushes in West Tian-Shan (
<figureCitation id="939710C82668FFC4FDC6AFB3B80FF867" box="[568,628,1989,2013]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-19@1.[151,1436,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Scoparia juldusellus. 1—male, Kara-Buura River valley; 2—male, Dolon Pass; 3—male genitalia, Kara-Buura valley, ventral view (aedeagus removed); 4—the same, aedeagus; 5, 6—habitats in Kyrgyzstan (5—Dolon Pass, Inner Tien- Shan; 6—Kara-Buura River valley, West Tien-Shan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457244" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457244/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="597">fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="5FD35CC52669FFC5FF69AF18B8C8F874" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457244" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6457244" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457244/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" startId="1.[151,264,1902,1926]" targetBox="[151,1436,181,1878]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="0B130C4D2669FFC5FF69AF18B8C8F874" blockId="1.[151,1437,1902,1998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2669FFC5FF69AF18BB41F83C" bold="true" box="[151,314,1902,1926]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">FIGURES 1–6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="CCAC77CE2669FFC5FEC1AF18B875F83C" baseAuthorityName="Caradja" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[319,526,1902,1926]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Scoparia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juldusellus">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F2669FFC5FEC1AF18B875F83C" box="[319,526,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Scoparia juldusellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 1—male, Kara-Buura River valley; 2—male, Dolon Pass; 3—male genitalia, Kara-Buura valley, ventral view (aedeagus removed); 4—the same, aedeagus; 5, 6—habitats in Kyrgyzstan (5—Dolon Pass, Inner Tien-Shan; 6—Kara-Buura River valley, West Tien-Shan).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="43B65FC6266AFFC6FF39A8E1BE85FF4D" pageId="2" pageNumber="599" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0B130C4D266AFFC6FF39A8E1BE85FF4D" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F266AFFC6FF39A8E1BBDDFF0A" box="[199,422,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="599" reason="1">
<emphasis id="39D8D05F266AFFC6FF39A8E1BB37FF15" bold="true" box="[199,332,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="599">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="939710C8266AFFC6FEA2A8E1BBE2FF0A" box="[348,409,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1070,1094]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,272,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1436,272,1046]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 7. Distribution of Scoparia juldusellus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457246" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457246/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="599">fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
To date, the species was known only from its 
<typeStatus id="D417B2EF266AFFC6FC61A8EEB9B6FF0A" box="[927,973,152,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="599">type</typeStatus>
locality. Our data enlarged its area significantly, now it is known also from Talas Mts (Kara-Buura River) in West Tian-Shan and from Baidulu Mts (Dolon Pass) in Inner Tian-Shan (
<collectingCountry id="73BB4CDD266AFFC6FEACA896BBA8FF42" box="[338,467,224,248]" name="Kyrgyzstan" pageId="2" pageNumber="599">Kyrgyzstan</collectingCountry>
). We can assume its wider distribution in the montane areas of Central Asia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
